To create a simple website structure for the village Valgjärve in Estonia including a navbar with a logo and links to other pages such as the About page, Blog, and Donation page, you will need to update the given HTML code and add the necessary elements. Also, since Estonia's official language is Estonian, you should change the `lang` attribute to `et` for Estonian.

Here is an updated version of the HTML with the navbar added and placeholders for the logo and page links:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="et">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Valgjärve küla</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
</head>
<body>
    <header>
        <nav class="navbar">
            <a href="/" class="navbar-brand">
                <img src="images/logo.png" alt="Valgjärve logo">
            </a>
            <ul class="navbar-nav">
                <li class="nav-item"><a href="index.html" class="nav-link">Avaleht</a></li>
                <li class="nav-item"><a href="about.html" class="nav-link">Meist</a></li>
                <li class="nav-item"><a href="blog.html" class="nav-link">Blogi</a></li>
                <li class="nav-item"><a href="donate.html" class="nav-link">Toetamine</a></li>
            </ul>
        </nav>
    </header>

    <main>
        <!-- Content for each page here -->
    </main>

    <footer>
        <!-- Footer content here -->
    </footer>

    <script src="script.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

Remember to create additional pages (`about.html`, `blog.html`, `donate.html`) corresponding to the links in the navbar.

Also, you'll need to create a `styles.css` file to handle the styling of your website. Here's an example of how it might look:

```css
/* styles.css */

body {
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
}

.navbar {
    background-color: #333;
    color: white;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    padding: 1rem;
}

.navbar-brand img {
    height: 50px; /* Logo size */
}

.navbar-nav {
    list-style: none;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    display: flex;
}

.nav-item {
    margin-left: 1rem;
}

.nav-link {
    color: white;
    text-decoration: none;
    padding: 0.5rem 1rem;
}

.nav-link:hover {
    background-color: #555;
}

main {
    padding: 20px;
}

footer {
    background-color: #333;
    color: white;
    text-align: center;
    padding: 1rem;
    position: relative;
    bottom: 0;
    width: 100%;
}
```

This CSS file includes basic styling. You will need to develop it further and adjust it to match the desired aesthetics for the Valgjärve village website.

Nginx does not support placing configuration files inside arbitrary project directories for routing and serving content. Its configuration is centralized within its own configuration directory, typically found in `/etc/nginx/`. However, there are ways you can organize your project files to make it easier to manage Nginx server block configurations for each project.

Here are a couple of organizational strategies:

### Using Includes in Nginx Configuration
You can include a specific configuration snippet within your main `server` block configuration that references a configuration file located in your project directory for additional settings. This approach allows you to isolate some aspects of the configuration to your project directory.

For instance:
- First, in your main server block file for the project in `/etc/nginx/sites-available/valgjarve`, you include a line to import the snippet:
    ```nginx
    server {
        listen 80;
        server_name valgjarve.local;

        root /home/yourusername/Documents/valgjarve;
        index index.html;

        include /home/yourusername/Documents/valgjarve/nginx_project_conf.conf;

        location / {
            try_files $uri $uri/ =404;
        }
    }
    ```
- Then, you would create the `nginx_project_conf.conf` file within your project directory (`/home/yourusername/Documents/valgjarve/`), and Nginx will include those settings when processing the configuration.

### Symbolic Links for Convenience
Rather than copying your server block files around, consider placing the server block configuration files in the `/etc/nginx/sites-available/` directory and creating a symbolic link to that file within your project directory.

For example:
```shell
ln -s /etc/nginx/sites-available/valgjarve /home/yourusername/Documents/valgjarve/nginx_site_config
```

Now, within your project directory, you have `nginx_site_config` as a symbolic link to the actual configuration file. While you still need administrative privileges to edit the file, this provides a quick path to it from your project directory.

It's important to understand that for security reasons, Nginx is designed to only consider configuration files in its specified directories. Modifying the central configuration is a task that typically requires root or superuser privileges to prevent unauthorized changes to how the web server operates. The recommended best practice is to manage your web server configurations within the directories intended for them, typically `/etc/nginx/`.

Remember to execute `sudo nginx -t` to test your configuration anytime you make changes, and reload Nginx using `sudo systemctl reload nginx` or `sudo nginx -s reload` to apply the new configuration.

Yes, there are web servers that allow for a decentralized configuration approach closer to what you're describing. One popular example is Node.js with the Express.js framework, which allows you to define routing and server configurations directly within your project's codebase.

When using Node.js and Express, you can set up an HTTP server along with its routes directly in your project directory. Each Node.js project has its own `package.json` that keeps track of dependencies and can include start scripts to run your server.

Here's a basic example of how an Express.js server might look like, with its configuration stored within the project directory:

```javascript
// app.js
const express = require('express');
const app = express();
const port = 3000;

app.use(express.static('public'));

app.get('/', (req, res) => {
  res.send('Welcome to Valgjärve Village Website!');
});

// Additional routes here...

app.listen(port, () => {
  console.log(`Server running at http://localhost:${port}/`);
});
```

The `public` directory would hold all your static files like HTML, CSS, and JavaScript, and you can define dynamic routes directly in your `app.js` file.

To start this server, you'd just run `node app.js` from within your project directory, and your configuration would be as portable as your project code.

Another example is PHP with its built-in development server, which can be invoked with the following command:

```sh
php -S localhost:8000 -t /path/to/your/project
```

This command tells PHP to start a simple web server serving the files from `/path/to/your/project` on `localhost` at port `8000`.

Please note, these development servers are not designed for production use. They are useful for development and testing but lack the robustness, security, and performance tuning necessary for a production environment.

For production use, you would still typically deploy to a more scalable and secure server. In such cases, you might use services like Docker to containerize your app along with its environment, or platforms like Heroku where you can push your code and let the platform handle the deployment and server configuration. These tools can help maintain configuration consistency across different environments and make deployment simpler.

It's important to pick a server solution that fits your project's needs and your operational workflow. If keeping configuration data inside your project's directory is crucial, look into solutions like Node.js with Express, PHP's built-in server for development, or consider containerization with Docker for production.
